49
00:01:32,479 --> 00:01:34,070
Hey, last year it said

50
00:01:34,070 --> 00:01:35,609
hashtag live your beauty

51
00:01:35,609 --> 00:01:38,719
and had a woman staring lovingly at a shoe.

52
00:01:38,719 --> 00:01:41,070
So I’d say that girl power is better.

53
00:01:41,070 --> 00:01:43,429
That’s not what I had in mind.

54
00:01:43,429 --> 00:01:44,829
What about the Me Too movement

55
00:01:44,829 --> 00:01:47,229
to raise awareness about sexual harassment?

56
00:01:47,229 --> 00:01:49,189
Is that having an impact at all?

57
00:01:49,189 --> 00:01:51,259
Yes, sort of.

58
00:01:51,259 --> 00:01:52,659
Me Too made a splash in China

59
00:01:52,659 --> 00:01:53,659
earlier this year,

60
00:01:53,659 --> 00:01:55,149
when a Chinese woman named Luo Xixi

61
00:01:55,149 --> 00:01:57,679
posted online story of how she was

62
00:01:57,679 --> 00:01:59,570
studying under a famous professor,

63
00:01:59,570 --> 00:02:01,209
Chen Xiaowu.

64
00:02:02,209 --> 00:02:03,209
She says he tried to coerce her

65
00:02:03,209 --> 00:02:04,399
into having sex with him.

66
00:02:04,399 --> 00:02:06,149
He only stopped when she told him

67
00:02:06,149 --> 00:02:07,569
she was a virgin.

68
00:02:07,569 --> 00:02:09,069
More women also accused Chen,

69
00:02:09,069 --> 00:02:10,149
and even state-run media

70
00:02:10,149 --> 00:02:12,069
started reporting on the story.

71
00:02:12,069 --> 00:02:13,519
Chen was eventually fired.

72
00:02:13,519 --> 00:02:14,519
Wow.

73
00:02:14,519 --> 00:02:15,700
I’m surprised it actually worked.

74
00:02:15,700 --> 00:02:17,599
Does that mean Me Too

75
00:02:17,599 --> 00:02:20,970
is growing into a movement in China?

76
00:02:20,970 --> 00:02:21,970
No.

77
00:02:21,970 --> 00:02:22,970
It’s complicated.

78
00:02:22,970 --> 00:02:24,500
More women started sharing stories online

79
00:02:24,500 --> 00:02:27,370
of being harassed by their college professors,

80
00:02:27,370 --> 00:02:28,530
but soon the words Me Too

81
00:02:28,530 --> 00:02:31,650
started getting censored online.

82
00:02:31,650 --> 00:02:33,450
So now it’s censored?

83
00:02:33,450 --> 00:02:34,450
No.

84
00:02:34,450 --> 00:02:35,720
It’s complicated.

85
00:02:35,720 --> 00:02:36,720
Chinese women started using

86
00:02:36,720 --> 00:02:38,900
the hashtag rice bunny instead,

87
00:02:38,900 --> 00:02:40,370
because those words sound like

88
00:02:40,370 --> 00:02:42,170
Me Too in Chinese.

89
00:02:42,170 --> 00:02:43,680
And you can still find articles

90
00:02:43,680 --> 00:02:44,680
on the Chinese internet

91
00:02:44,680 --> 00:02:46,190
that discuss the Me Too movement.

92
00:02:46,190 --> 00:02:47,660
Wait a minute.

93
00:02:47,660 --> 00:02:48,780
Why would the Chinese Communist Party

94
00:02:48,780 --> 00:02:50,490
allow reporting on this,

95
00:02:50,490 --> 00:02:51,790
but then censor it,

96
00:02:51,790 --> 00:02:54,090
and then not censor it?

97
00:02:54,090 --> 00:02:56,540
It’s a way of staying in control.

98
00:02:56,540 --> 00:02:57,680
They start off by letting people

99
00:02:57,680 --> 00:02:59,750
talk about sexual harassment,

100
00:02:59,750 --> 00:03:01,130
and they’re even ok with action

101
00:03:01,130 --> 00:03:03,450
being taken in isolated cases,

102
00:03:03,450 --> 00:03:05,299
like Chen getting fired.

103
00:03:05,299 --> 00:03:07,200
But then when it gets too popular,

104
00:03:07,200 --> 00:03:08,200
they censor it.

105
00:03:08,200 --> 00:03:09,280
It’s a warning to people

106
00:03:09,280 --> 00:03:12,110
that this topic is getting too sensitive.

107
00:03:12,110 --> 00:03:14,019
But they don’t want to completely cut off

108
00:03:14,019 --> 00:03:15,329
all discussion of it because

109
00:03:15,329 --> 00:03:16,409
then people would notice

110
00:03:16,409 --> 00:03:18,280
that they can’t talk about it.

111
00:03:18,280 --> 00:03:21,739
That is so...complicated.

112
00:03:21,739 --> 00:03:23,720
What is even the point of doing that?

113
00:03:23,720 --> 00:03:24,840
Two things:

114
00:03:24,840 --> 00:03:26,099
One, they want to make people

115
00:03:26,099 --> 00:03:27,650
think that authorities are doing

116
00:03:27,650 --> 00:03:29,170
something about the issue.

117
00:03:29,170 --> 00:03:30,500
When state-run media talked about

118
00:03:30,500 --> 00:03:31,500
Chen being fired,

119
00:03:31,500 --> 00:03:33,530
they emphasized that “the quick response

120
00:03:33,530 --> 00:03:35,510
and strong stance of the Chinese authorities

121
00:03:35,510 --> 00:03:38,129
won applause from the public.”

122
00:03:38,129 --> 00:03:39,530
But then they go and censor it.

123
00:03:39,530 --> 00:03:40,930
So doesn’t that make it look like

124
00:03:40,930 --> 00:03:43,430
they’re not really doing something about
it?

125
00:03:43,430 --> 00:03:45,570
Yes, but the censorship is important

126
00:03:45,570 --> 00:03:47,120
for point number two.

127
00:03:47,120 --> 00:03:48,439
The Communist Party doesn’t want

128
00:03:48,439 --> 00:03:51,000
grassroots movements to get too popular.

129
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:52,920
They care way more about social control

130
00:03:52,920 --> 00:03:55,939
than really exposing sexual harassment in
China.

131
00:03:55,939 --> 00:03:57,370
Especially when it involves

132
00:03:57,370 --> 00:03:59,840
exposing Chinese officials.

133
00:03:59,840 --> 00:04:01,969
So when people start petitions about the issue,

134
00:04:01,969 --> 00:04:04,290
well, those have to be censored.

135
00:04:04,290 --> 00:04:05,900
And whatever discussion is happening

136
00:04:05,900 --> 00:04:08,459
is also only happening online.

137
00:04:08,459 --> 00:04:09,459
Like three years ago,

138
00:04:09,459 --> 00:04:12,069
there were five women who were arrested for,

139
00:04:12,069 --> 00:04:13,069
